'updated_at': '2022-03-24T21:14:16Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': '
This article is not consistent in how it outlines whether role requirements, sometimes using OR, sometimes using Commas, sometimes using a "/", and sometimes using + (for AND).

It is confusing customers whether "/" and "," mean "OR" or whether they mean "AND".  Can we find a way to be more clear when we mean OR and AND?

Eg
Review Pipeline Runs uses a "/" which i believe represents OR

Review pipeline runs | Synapse Artifact Publisher/Synapse Contributor

While "List and open any published SQL script" uses "," which I believe represents OR

Synapse Artifact User, Artifact Publisher, Synapse Contributor

Feedback from customers is that this is confusing.  Given the importance of the security model in a production environment it is key that this document is very clear and straightforward.  Could we consider being consistent with OR and AND to drive clarity in the role requirements?

---

'updated_at': '2022-03-23T21:26:19Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': "I've lost several hours in this page.

### Partitioned parquet

Most commonly used data type in 2022 is partitioned parquet datasets. The conclusion for a dedicated SQL pool is: you can't use  them as the values of your partition columns will be lost. This is not clear from this page.

### COPY INTO as alternative

COPY INTO might often be a good alternative and even allows you to skip the schema definition since it can auto-create tables. This page should have mentioned  that so that I know that there are alternatives that might better fit my use case.

### No clear idea what I should use

Should I use hadoop or should I use native? I still don't know. Some rows say _yes_ on both sides, but then they contain a comment? What do these rows even mean? What is _Storage filter pushdown_? What is _Folder partition elimination_? Etc. Not having this page would have been as useful as having it.

---

On the link for the docs regarding the quickstart deployment of an Azure Synapse workspace, we have a warning Note claiming that you cannot create a Synapse Analytics Workspace in a CSP subscription:

https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/synapse-analytics/quickstart-create-workspace

"After creating your Azure Synapse workspace, you will not be able to move the workspace to another Azure Active Directory tenant. If you do so through subscription migration or other actions, you may lose access to the artifacts within the workspace. Additionally, you currently cannot create a Synapse Analytics workspace in a [Cloud Solution Provider (CSP)](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/partner-center/csp-overview) subscription."

I believe this is wrong and may have been left as a mistake, since you can create Synapse Workspaces under CSP subscriptions and there are price listings for the full Synapse product as well.

Hopefully you can change this so that Partners don't get mistaken by it.

Thank you and have a good day,

doc.
1. Added wheel package to workspace
1. Added wheel package to spark pool
1. The spark pool is restarted between those changes.

The documentation is lacking information about what should happen when you have multiple versions of the wheel package in either the workspace or the pool. My expectation was that latest package version would be used, but what I'm experiencing is that the package with older version number continues to be used. That's an odd behaviour that the documentation should mention.
